            <exercisegroup> <title> Area of a Triangle </title>
				<introduction>
					<p>
						Recall that in Euclidean geometry the area of a triangle with side lengths <m> a </m>, <m> b </m> and <m> c </m> can be found using Heron's formula:
						<me> \text{Area}=\sqrt{s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)} </me>
						where <m> s=\frac{1}{2}(a+b+c) </m>.
					</p>
				</introduction>

				<exercise>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Find the (Euclidean) area of the triangle whose vertices are <m> A=(0,0) </m>, <m> B=(3,0) </m>, <m> C=(0,3) </m>.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<answer>
						<p>
							
						</p>
					</answer>
				</exercise>

